LABS
Hemoglobin 12.4.  Leukocytes 12.2.  Platelet count 216.  Sodium and potassium within normal range.  Glucose 138.  Creatinine 0.8.  Bicarb 20. C-reactive protein was 21.7, and CA125 was 50 on February 22, 2010.  Notably there was no CEA done.
IMPRESSION/REPORT/PLAN
#1 Stage III TNM stage sigmoid colon cancer (T4, N2, with 6/32 regional lymph nodes involve by metastatic adenocarcinoma)
KRAS mutation status pending.
PLAN
The next step was discussed in detail with Mrs. Nance.  An approach would be to give FOLFOX therapy four to six-weeks from surgery provided there is an uneventful postoperative course.  After adequate time for wound healing, FOLFOX 6 regimen can be administered.  The side-effects of therapy including, but not limited to, mucositis, diarrhea, myelosuppression, peripheral neuropathy, nausea, vomiting, infection, death were discussed with Mrs. Nance.  There is a low likelihood of alopecia less than 5% with this regimen.  In addition, she would require a port placement, and I would discuss with the primary team if this can be performed during her current admission. We would be also inclined to get her evaluated by a medical geneticist.  I do note that DNA mismatch repair enzyme immunohistochemical staining (MLH1, MSH2, MSH6, PMS2) showed intact expression of all four enzymes thereby suggesting that hereditary nonpolyposis colorectal cancer syndrome is unlikely.  However based on her family history and multiple polyps, a few of which are dysplastic, other diagnoses such as attenuated familial adenomatosis polyposis could be entertained.  It would be worthwhile to get a consultation from medical geneticist, and we would arrange for that.  In addition, I would try to obtain a CEA level from the preoperative sample if possible, otherwise from todays' sample.  I have already asked the path lab to add KRAS mutation analysis which would be helpful with regard to future therapy with cetuximab.  If she is Wild type KRAS (absence of mutation) cetuximab would be a useful agent in future.  We would set-up an appointment with Medical Oncology in four to six-weeks.
The case was discussed extensively with Dr. Davis

