[start section id="20103"]

Mrs. Nance is a very pleasant 42-year-old nurse from 52349 who underwent hand-assisted sigmoid resection with mid-rectal anastomosis on March 2, 2010, due to recent diagnosis of sigmoid colon cancer.  She was diagnosed with colon cancer on a recent colonoscopy that demonstrated a nonobstructing tumor lesion in the sigmoid colon.  In addition, on that colonoscopy several polyps were found and in particular a sessile polyp in the ascending colon was suggestive of tubular adenoma with low-grade dysplasia.  Another tubular adenoma with low-grade dysplasia was found on mid-transverse colon.  Multiple other polyps were noted both in transverse colon, and there were areas of inflammatory reaction in the mucosa of sigmoid colon.  Most importantly, an ulcerating, fungating tumor was noted (at 20 to 23 cm) which showed an infiltrating grade 2/4 adenocarcinoma.  Her recent surgical resections were suggestive of pT3N2 lesion as an invasive grade 3 of 4 adenocarcinoma was identified forming an ulcerative polypoid mass located 4.5-cm from rectal mucosal margin.  The tumor invaded through muscularis propria and into the pericolic fat.  Lymphatic vascular invasion was absent, and all surgical margins were negative for dysplasia and tumor.  A total of 21 cm of sigmoid colon and rectum were resected.
Presenting symptoms: Mrs. Nance had been noticing blood in her stool mixed with mucus for the last one-year along with a change in the caliber size of her stools for the last six-months.  In addition, she had been complaining of bloating for the last six-months.  She had an essentially negative CT-scan of the abdomen and pelvis on February 8, 2010.  There was no CEA level drawn.  She denies any fever, chills, loss of appetite, or weight-loss.  She denies any chest pain currently but was more recently evaluated with a treadmill stress test for a left shoulder pain.  Apparently she was cleared for surgery, although she did not complete the stress test due to elevated blood pressure and fatigue.

